{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585955"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15040"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15040"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0,0.19,0.14,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67231"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67231"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERhabdomyolysis is a condition characterized by skeletal muscle breakdown and release of intracellular contents into circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory findings typically include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EElevated serum creatine kinase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EElevated serum potassium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EElevated serum phosphate\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic finding in rhabdomyolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tea-coloured urine with positive blood on dipstick","Green-coloured urine with negative blood on dipstick","Clear urine with high protein content","Orange urine with positive bilirubin","Brown urine with positive glucose"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn rhabdomyolysis, damaged skeletal muscle releases myoglobin into circulation, resulting in \u003Cstrong\u003Etea-coloured urine with positive blood on dipstick\u003C/strong\u003E. The positive dipstick occurs because myoglobin cross-reacts with the blood testing pad, despite no red blood cells being present on microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreen-coloured urine with negative blood on dipstick\u003C/strong\u003E - Green urine is not associated with rhabdomyolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClear urine with high protein content\u003C/strong\u003E - Myoglobinuria causes distinctively dark urine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrange urine with positive bilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E - Orange urine suggests bile pigments rather than myoglobin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrown urine with positive glucose\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose positivity is not a feature of rhabdomyolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther key features of rhabdomyolysis include markedly elevated creatine kinase, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, and risk of acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rhabdomyolysis presents with tea-coloured urine due to myoglobin release from damaged skeletal muscle.","Urine dipstick tests positive for blood in rhabdomyolysis due to myoglobin cross-reactivity, despite absence of red blood cells.","Rhabdomyolysis causes elevated creatine kinase and hyperkalaemia due to muscle cell breakdown."],"references":["Stahl K, Rastelli E, Schoser B. A systematic review on the definition of rhabdomyolysis. J Neurol. 2020 Apr;267(4):877-882. doi: 10.1007/s00415-019-09185-4. Epub 2019 Jan 7. PMID: 30617905.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15040"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T09:14:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:16:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67231"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh